Bottom line: Veeva posted a solid top and bottom- line beat, with total revenue of \(\) 789.1\(mn (+17\% y / y)\) versus expectations of \(- \S 768mn\) \((+13.6\%)\) , driven by strength in Crossix on the commercial side and broad- based momentum across R&D. EPS also came in ahead of consensus at \(\) 1.99\(vs.\) \ \(1.90\) . That said, billings landed just shy of expectations at \(\) 666m\(versus consensus of\) \ \(666.5m\) , which is contributing to a modest pullback in the stock following a strong \(40\%\) YTD run. However, mgmt. nudged FY26 guidance higher across the board. Total revenue was raised by \(\) 40m\(to a new range of\) \ \(3.134-\) \(\) 3.140\(bn. Operating income guidance increased\) \ \(28m\) to \(\) 1.388bn\(and normalized billings was raised\) \ \(35m\) from the prior outlook to \(\) 3.355bn\(. We are bumping our PT to\) \ \(295\) or \(28x\) EV/CY26 FCF to account for the raised guidance. Other highlights from the quarter include: 1) The IQVIA partnership brings multiple layers of benefits for VEEV that should unfold over time. In the near term, the ability for customers to seamlessly incorporate IQVIA data into VEEV workflows is most impactful for Veeva Nitro, enhancing its value in commercial analytics. This also helps reduce past customer friction from dealing with multiple vendors. Over time, as sales teams learn to leverage this advantage, we see it becoming a tailwind for revenue growth in later years; 2) Two additional top - 20 biopharmas have given verbal commitments to VEEV, bringing the total to 9 of the top 20, while CRM secured another verbal commitment, bringing its total to 3. With 12 of the top 20 now committed, we believe it's increasingly likely that a majority will sign on by year - end, particularly as implementation timelines begin to add pressure; 3) Crossix was the key driver of commercial solutions growth, with revenue up \(13\% y / y\) to \(\) 307.5m\(. Measurement continues to deliver predictable revenue growth, while audiences are benefiting from stronger execution - helping to smooth out what has historically been a lumpier business; 4) Billings came in at\) \ \(666m\) , modestly below consensus of \(\) 666.5m\(. Mgmt. cited customer - specific and operational factors as drivers of the lumpiness. Importantly, though, full - year FY26 billings guidance was raised by\) \ \(35m\) to \(\) 3.355bn\(, reinforcing confidence in the outlook, and 5) Vault migrations appear to be progressing well, with two top - 20 biopharmas now live - one in the U.S. and the other in Europe. If these implementations proceed smoothly, we believe this should meaningfully strengthen VEEV's case with the 8 remaining top - 20 biopharmas, as they'll have a strong set of use cases to show.

Recapping the quarter: Veeva reported total revenue of \(- \S 789.1m\) \((+17\% y / y)\) , which was above our/Street estimates of \(\) 766m\(/\) \ \(768m\) . Subscription revenue of \(\) 659.2m\(\) (17\% y / y)\) was also above our/Street estimates of \(- \S 649m\) , and professional services revenue came in at \(\) 129.9m\(+13\% y / y)\) ahead of our/Street estimates of \(- \S 117.0m / \S 118.4m\) . EPS of \(\) 1.99\(came in above our/Street estimates of\) \ \(1.89 / \S 1.90\) . Operating margin of \(44.7\%\) came in above our/Street estimates of \(43.8\%\) . Billings were up \(10\% y / y\) to \(\) 666.0m\(below consensus of\) \ \(666.5m\) .
Billing volatility Crossix dynamics Potential IQVIA tailwinds OBBB implications

1) The IQVIA partnership brings multiple layers of benefits for VEEV that should unfold over time. In the near term, the ability for customers to seamlessly incorporate IQVIA data into VEEV workflows is most impactful for Veeva Nitro, enhancing its value in commercial analytics. This also helps reduce past customer friction from dealing with multiple vendors. Over time, as sales teams learn to leverage this advantage, we see it becoming a tailwind for revenue growth in later years.

2) Two additional top-20 biopharmas have given verbal commitments to VEEV, bringing the total to 9 of the top 20, while CRM secured another verbal commitment, bringing its total to 3. With 12 of the top 20 now committed, we believe it's increasingly likely that a majority will sign on by year-end, particularly as implementation timelines begin to add pressure.

3) Crossix was the key driver of commercial solutions growth, with revenue up \(13\%\) y/y to \(\) 307.5\(mn. Measurement continues to deliver predictable revenue growth, while audiences are benefiting from stronger execution - - helping to smooth out what has historically been a lumpier business.

4) Billings came in at \(\) 666\(mn, modestly below consensus of\) \ \(666.5mn\) . Mgmt. cited customerspecific and operational factors as drivers of the lumpiness. Importantly, though, full-year FY26 billings guidance was raised by \(\) 35\(mn to\) \ \(3.355bn\) , reinforcing confidence in the outlook.

5) Vault migrations appear to be progressing well, with two top-20 biopharmas now live - - one in the U.S. and the other in Europe. If these implementations proceed smoothly, we believe this should meaningfully strengthen VEEV's case with the 8 remaining top-20 biopharmas, as they'll have a strong set of use cases to show.

Evercore ISI's recommendations are based on a stock's total forecasted return over the next 12 months. Total forecasted return is equal to the expected percentage price return plus gross dividend yield. We divide our stocks under coverage into three primary ratings categories, with the following return guidelines:

Outperform- the total forecasted return is expected to be greater than the expected total return of the analyst's coverage sector. In Line- the total forecasted return is expected to be in line with the expected total return of the analyst's coverage sector. Underperform- the total forecasted return is expected to be less than the expected total return of the analyst's coverage sector. Coverage Suspended- the rating and target price have been removed pursuant to Evercore ISI policy when Evercore is acting in an advisory capacity in a merger or strategic transaction involving this company and in certain other circumstances. Rating Suspended- Evercore ISI has suspended the rating and target price for this stock because there is not sufficient fundamental basis for determining, or there are legal, regulatory or policy constraints around publishing, a rating or target price. The previous rating and target price, if any, are no longer in effect for this company and should not be relied upon.
Prior to October 10, 2015, the "Coverage Suspended" and "Rating Suspended" categories were included in the category "Suspended."

FINRA requires that members who use a ratings system with terms other than "Buy," "Hold/Neutral" and "Sell" to equate their own ratings to these categories. For this purpose, and in the Evercore ISI ratings distribution below, our Outperform, In Line, and Underperform ratings can be equated to Buy, Hold and Sell, respectively.
